Hi Jimmy,

I think h is right, because we previously use H to mean the change in aquifer storage (i.e. an amount of water), while we use h to mean the depth to groundwater from the surface. Hence in a soil column H represents the change in depth and h represents the absolute depth from the top of the surface.

I know what you mean about line 234, but I think M is correct because we use M here to mean mass. This appears to be the convention the reviewer wanted us to adopt (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensional_analysis), whereby M indicates a mass, L is length and T is time (the idea being that the dimensions of all physical variables can be expressed in terms of these base dimensions). In order to be consistent we have to use units of mass rather than volume. In practice it doesn't make any difference because 1m3=1000kg water, and hence the values remain the same if the units are used consistently.

I hope this makes sense. It's a long time since I did any kind of dimensional analysis. The reviewer is clearly an engineer!

S

